  "insights": {
    "title": "Insights on Antenatal Care",
    "subtitle": "AI-generated insights based on National Demographic and Health Survey data on antenatal care",
    "overview": "The regional picture suggests that many women are reaching antenatal care at least once, but the bigger divide opens when care has to continue through repeated visits and protective measures. In 2025, Western Visayas reached 98.5 percent for receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider, while BARMM was at 57.2 percent. The contrast becomes even sharper at 8+ ANC visits, where Central Visayas reached 64.3 percent and BARMM was at 14.0 percent.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Some regions are much farther along than others",
        "body": "Western Visayas stands out for broad strength across the set of measures, with 98.5 percent receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider, 91.3 percent reaching 4+ visits, 97.7 percent taking iron supplements, and 82.8 percent reporting protection against neonatal tetanus. NCR, CALABARZON, and Central Visayas also post strong figures on several measures. BARMM sits apart on the other end, at 57.2 percent for receiving skilled antenatal care, 43.3 percent for 4+ visits, 14.0 percent for 8+ visits, 62.6 percent for iron supplements, and 54.8 percent for neonatal tetanus protection. For families in these regions, the difference is not about one missing service but about a much thinner pattern of care across pregnancy."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Starting care and staying in care are not the same thing",
        "body": "Several regions look much stronger on first contact than on sustained care. Ilocos Region reached 94.3 percent for receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider, but only 78.4 percent reached 4+ visits and 22.5 percent reached 8+ visits. Zamboanga Peninsula shows a similar drop, from 87.1 percent receiving care to 22.8 percent at 8+ visits, and Northern Mindanao falls from 78.5 percent to 16.1 percent. Central Visayas reads very differently: only 76.0 percent are recorded as receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider, but 94.0 percent reached 4+ visits and 64.3 percent reached 8+ visits. The survey does not explain why these paths differ, but it does show that a high first-contact figure does not automatically mean women are being carried through a longer schedule of care."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Protection does not always rise with service contact",
        "body": "The protective measures add another layer to the story. CAR recorded 95.6 percent for receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider, but neonatal tetanus protection was 71.3 percent. Caraga posted 94.3 percent for 4+ visits, yet neonatal tetanus protection was 69.5 percent. Western Visayas combines high contact with high protection, while other places show that strong attendance on visits does not always travel with equally strong protection. That matters because families experience pregnancy care as a package, not as separate indicators."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Schooling and household resources still separate families sharply",
        "body": "The background breakdowns show that these gaps are not only regional. In 2025, women with Grades 1-6 education were at 76.1 percent for receiving antenatal care from a skilled provider and just 14.7 percent for 8+ visits, compared with 95.0 percent and 53.2 percent among women with college education. The wealth gradient is similarly steep. Women in the lowest quintile were at 80.0 percent for receiving skilled antenatal care and 20.7 percent for 8+ visits, while those in the highest quintile were at 95.6 percent and 67.5 percent. Iron supplementation also ranged from 80.7 percent in the lowest quintile to 97.8 percent in the highest. The biggest separation shows up not at the first point of contact, but in whether women are able to sustain care through pregnancy."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Younger mothers are closer on first contact than on follow-through",
        "body": "Among mothers younger than 20, 84.6 percent received antenatal care from a skilled provider and 82.2 percent reached 4+ visits in 2025. But only 25.8 percent reached 8+ visits. That is well below the 42.8 percent recorded among mothers aged 20-34 and the 37.0 percent among those aged 35-49. The younger group is therefore not far behind on first contact, but it falls much further behind once care is measured as a longer process over pregnancy."
      },
      {
        "heading": "From 2022 to 2025, the clearest gains are in 8+ visits",
        "body": "The strongest movement from 2022 to 2025 appears in the 8+ visit measure. Among mothers aged 20-34, 8+ ANC visits rose from 29.0 percent to 42.8 percent. Among women with post-secondary education, the figure rose from 33.3 percent to 54.2 percent, and in the middle wealth quintile it rose from 28.8 percent to 44.4 percent. The lowest quintile also improved, from 12.6 percent to 20.7 percent, though it remained far behind the rest. Not every indicator moved the same way over the same period. Neonatal tetanus protection fell in several groups, including among women with Grades 7-10 education and in the middle wealth quintile, so the recent picture is one of progress in repeated visits alongside a more mixed pattern on protection."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Regional differences in antenatal care are wide, and BARMM remains far behind the strongest-performing regions across the full set of measures.",
      "The biggest divide is often not whether women begin care, but whether they stay connected long enough to reach 8+ visits and other protective care.",
      "From 2022 to 2025, repeated ANC visits improved more clearly than neonatal tetanus protection, so the gains are real but uneven."
    ]
